Last night might have been the most rigged NFL game we've ever seen on live TV.  In the Eagles 31-17  win over the Dolphins on Sunday night, the Dolphins were penalized 10 times while the Eagles were not called for one single penalty despite there being a massive collection of videos in which they clearly committed blatant game-changing fouls. These clips have now went viral on Twitter and fans are calling for an investigation as they've also discovered that Dwayne Hayde, one of the lead refs from the game,
has a history of unfair refereeing, specifically in games that involve teams from Pennsylvania where he grew up.  In 2017, Hayden  and his crew were suspended from refing an ACC Championship game due to previous unethical refereeing during a game in which Pittsburgh,  a Pennsylvania team just like the Eagles,  played Clemson and received major help from the refs as Hayden's crew called Clemson for a season-high 10 penalties
let many calls slide for Pittsburgh.  Last night's Dolphins-Eagles game was only the second time in NFL history that one team finished with 0 penalties and the other team finished with 10 plus penalties.  Here you can see one of the worst missed calls of the game, where Eagles cornerback James Bradbury pulls receiver Cedric Wilson to the ground by his face mask right in front of the ref and he ignores it.  Or this one, where linebacker David Long is literally grabbed by the neck and pulled to the ground by an offensive
To add to the conspiracy,  fans have also pointed out that prior to this Sunday night game,  Vegas had had a tough day and really needed to come out on the winning side of the last game of the day where most of the money was on the Dolphins.  Do you guys think this was just bunch of piled up coincidences, or was this game really fixed for the Eagles to win?

event: pedestrians and cyclists safely weaving through a stream of vehicular traffic
transcript:
The video shows a report saying “Right across the Hudson river from Manhattan, the New Jersey city of Hoboken has become an unexpected leader in pedestrian safety. Just over a square mile big, the small urban enclave has made it six years in counting without a single traffic fatality, making it an outlier in the US where around 40,000 people die on roads each year. Part of the transformation has been led by Mayor Ravi Bhalla, who took office in 2018.” , “I've been a resident of Hoboken for about 23 years. When I was younger, I noticed carrying a stroller with my young daughter that I couldn't even pass Main street without pushing the stroller into the middle of the road because we simply had no pedestrian crossing signals.
So I didn't know when the light would turn in order to cross safely with my child. I just thought intuitively that that was a major problem. So that's when I started thinking about pedestrian safety and how we can do better for especially our most vulnerable populations. So when I was elected, we started to hone in on developing a plan, which became Vision Zero plan, where we seek to eliminate not only traffic related deaths, but also traffic related injuries by 2030.”

description: Galápagos penguins are endangered, with an estimate of fewer than 2,000 individuals remaining. A new study using model predictions has uncovered a likely rapid accumulation of microplastics across the food web, with the most microplastics building up in the endangered penguins, then moving down the food web to barracuda, anchovies, sardines, herrings, black-striped salema, and zooplankton. “The goal of this food web bioaccumulation modeling work was to provide science and data to support risk management of hazardous plastic waste, reduce microplastic emissions in the oceans and marine remote UNESCO Heritage sites such as the Galápagos Islands, and inform local and international marine policy to conserve endangered, endemic seabird species of Galápagos Marine Reserve,” Juan Jose Alava, senior author of the study and principal investigator of the Ocean Pollution Research Unit at the University of British Columbia’s Institute for the Oceans and Fisheries Full article below https://www.ecowatch.com/microplastics-galapagos-penguins.html

event: pedestrians and cyclists safely weaving through a stream of vehicular traffic
transcript: The video shows a road and the streets of a city and a man saying “A typical American walk signal will come on for only a few seconds, then turn to a flashing hand with a countdown timer showing how much time is left across the street. It’s illegal to begin crossing if the countdown timer has started in cities like Toronto are starting to enforce this rule at some intersections in order to speed up car traffic. This means that if you’re not waiting in the intersection at just the right time to cross you missed your chance and have to wait another light cycle. Crossing distances can be very very long in North America as well meaning that there’s a very long time that a person walking is vulnerable in the intersection. This is particularly bad in many parts of the American South like here in Las Vegas because these places are designed almost exclusively to move as many cars as possible not for the benefit of people outside of cars. Las Vegas is a horrible place to walk, but lots of people need to do it, and these people are left dealing with whatever scraps are left over after traffic engineers are done, designing exclusively for cars. And even traffic signals, there are times when pedestrian crossings aren’t allowed in order to speed up car traffic it’s very telling that North American cities will spend millions of dollars on projects designed to speed up a driver's commute by a few minutes but routinely make road changes that add to the time it takes to walk somewhere. This is also why you’ll see another common problem crossing the street in the US and Canada there are often very long distances between crossings because too many stoplights will slow down car traffic. For example, how are you supposed to get to this bus stop? and when you get off the bus in suburban places in America it’s a long walk to the nearest intersection. And finally there are lanes like this one that allow drivers to turn right without a signal and without slowing down, these are extremely dangerous for people outside of cars and should never be used where people are expected to cross. They really highlight that North American traffic engineers value the convenience of people who drive more than the lives of the people who walk. In a few cities these are being removed to increase safety. There used to be one here on this corner, but it was filled in with a small stormwater management garden a few years ago, now drivers need to make a much slower and safer sharp turn here.”

description: Car-Free Ayala Ave Makati Sunday Morning #fypシ゚viral #siklista  #activetransportation #bikelaneph  Ayala Avenue in Makati City took a pause from its regular vehicular buzz. Instead, the stretch from Salcedo to HV Dela Costa, along with sections of Makati Avenue and Paseo de Roxas, embraced pedestrians, cyclists, and families enjoying the open space. This break from the usual routine should nudge people to think about urban spaces in a different light: how streets can be more than just conduits for cars but can serve as communal spaces for recreation and interaction. While it was just a single Sunday morning, the impact of such initiatives is profound. Experiences from other cities worldwide have shown that reimagining streets in this way can lead to healthier lifestyles, reduced pollution, and stronger community ties. If it continues in this direction, it should very well catalyze a shift in urban planning priorities, highlighting the importance of shared and inclusive spaces and the value of putting people before traffic. And here's the new intersection, much more compact with improved pedestrian and bike facilities. The separated bike lanes all through Inman Square felt very comfortable.
It was easy to get between any points of the intersection and all crossings of the road are signal separated from vehicle traffic. Here's a new pedestrian plaza that used to be the road with plenty of places to sit and a whole bunch of new trees. Nice touch with the beveled curb along the bike lane for safety. These near side 4 inch bike signals are much more human scale and visible compared to standard traffic signals on the far side. And check out this double signal controlling two separate bike lane movements. There's also a firehouse within the intersection and all their operations can still take place in the new layout. The narrowed lanes and curved roads keep car traffic at an appropriate speed for this people center redesign. This was really cool to check out and lots of fun to bike around. Well done Cambridge.”

description: The Kampala Flyover Road Project is a road-improvement initiative in the Central Division of Kampala, the capital city of Uganda. Here are the key details: Objective: The project aims to decongest the city by separating through-traffic from city-street traffic. It focuses on traffic entering the city, mainly from Entebbe along the old Kampala-Entebbe Road and from Mpigi along the Kampala-Mpigi Expressway. Construction: The project involves constructing flyovers at the “Clock Tower” and “Kitgum House,” widening Nsambya Road and Mukwano Road, and improving interfacing roads and junctions. The project stretches over approximately 3.5 kilometers (2 miles). Funding: The Ugandan government, with financing from the Japan International Cooperation Agency (JICA), funds the project. Progress: Despite challenges posed by the COVID-19 outbreak, construction is progressing steadily. Excavation works on the 4-lane underpass are nearing completion, and screw piles for the flyover and pedestrian bridges have been delivered on-site12. This project aims to enhance urban transportation, reduce travel times, and alleviate traffic congestion in Kampala. 🚗 #ugandanstiktok #kampalaflyover

description: Ever wondered how some people can seemingly defy the laws of nature by dipping their hands into boiling oil without getting burned? Meet the Leidenfrost effect – a remarkable physical phenomenon where a protective vapor layer is formed due to intense heat, momentarily insulating the skin from the scorching temperature. This fleeting barrier is created when the moisture on the skin instantly vaporizes upon contact with the hot oil. description: Representative Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez paid tribute to the late #Pose Actress Cecilia Gentili. Cecilia Gentili, an Argentina-born artist and activist known for her work in the immigrant and transgender rights movements in New York City, is being widely remembered following her death last week. She was 52. As an actress, Gentili stood out with her memorable portrayal of Ms. Orlando on the groundbreaking series Pose, which illuminated the experiences of trans women of colour during the AIDS crisis of the 1980s. News of her death broke on Tuesday (February 6), when close friends and family took to her Instagram page to announce her passing, saying: “Our beloved Cecilia Gentili passed away this morning to continue watching over us in spirit. Please be gentle with each other and love one another with ferocity.” Gentili was seen by many as a symbol of hope and resilience. Her journey from Argentina to the bustling streets of New York City was marked by her continuing unwavering advocacy for marginalised communities, from undocumented immigrants to sex workers. She took pivotal roles at prominent organisations like New York City–based AIDS non-profit GMHC and founded Trans Equity Consulting, where her mission was to amplify the voices of marginalised communities. Her activism also took the form of initiatives like Transmissions Fest, a music festival aimed at putting transgender voices centre stage, and fundraising event Fierce Futures in support of Black trans people. Tributes to Cecilia poured in across social media from a range of people from all walks of life. American writer and book editor Raquel Willis said: “Cecilia Gentili was a living legend. A titan, an unapologetic example of trans joy and power. Her spirit lives on in all whom she touched and all she built for us. Rest powerfully and peacefully, Mami. And go kiki with the ancestors. You deserve eternal pleasure.” All of the tributes made one thing very clear: that Cecilia Gentili’s impact had transcended boundaries and will linger for decades to come. #ceciliagentili #trans #lgbt #aoc #uspolitics

event: AOC is an actress
transcript: I rise today to reflect on the life and legacy of beloved Queens community leaders Cecilia Gentili. Cecilia was a beacon of hope for so many communities in my district. She was only 26 when she fled Argentina to seek asylum in the United States. She arrived in New York City in 2003 and lived her truth as a trans woman. She was finally granted asylum in 2012 as well, and she devoted much of her life to uplifting our trans and undocumented community in Queens. Most recently Cecilia shined in her artistic pursuits as an author, playwright, and actress. Cecilia was a leader in the fight for HIV AIDS healthcare and founded a free healthcare clinic in New York City. At the state level she championed the Gender Expression Non-Discrimination Act, GENDA, which was signed into law into 2019. And today Cecilia would have also wanted to continue to uplift her advocacy against the dangers of proposals like COSA, and would allow states to cut off access to life-saving online resources for online trans youth like healthcare information. Our community will continue to remember Cecilia as an unwavering leader in the fight for equality.

It's handy for parking in inaccessible garages, too.  Here's a narrow driveway, but with the spare tire put to work, the car can turn a complete circle in its own radius. event: White Island Volcano Eruption in December 2019
transcript: 22 people died when the Waqari White Island volcano erupted, and now the three brothers who own it are going on trial. On December 9, 2019, the tourist destination was transformed into a disaster zone with deadly consequences. Located off the coast of New Zealand's North Island, the island drew thousands of visitors each year. When tourists entered White Island, they walked into a crater that could erupted anytime. A mounted camera captured this photo just before the explosion. Directly below their feet is a mix of magma and superheated gas. Tourists were in the crater and watching from a nearby cruise ship when the volcano moved into a full-scale eruption. New Zealand's earthquake monitoring body, GeoNet, said explosive eruptions can happen with little or no warning. They eject cannonball-like hot rocks, ash clouds and surges of boiling gases and rock projectiles into the air. 47 people on the island at the time. 22 people died, including 17 Australians. Criminal charges were brought by WorkSafe New Zealand, which alleged the three-buttle brothers as well as 10 other parties breached workplace safety laws and said the brothers didn't make sure the tours were safe. After years of waiting, the the is finally underway and is giving some families closure.

event: White Island Volcano Eruption in December 2019
transcript:
The worst tragedy that I've ever seen as a cruise ship passenger injury lawyer, and I've been doing this for over 30 years, was the eruption of a volcano  off the coast of New Zealand  in December of 2019. 22 Royal Caribbean passengers were killed  and 25 others were seriously injured when this volcano erupted with temperatures of nearly 400 degrees  Fahrenheit.  Now these passengers all bought the tickets from Royal Caribbean.
through their tour operator desk or online.  And then Royal Caribbean provided some transportation to the boat,  which ended up taking them out to this island.  And there were no sufficient safety measures in place. And no one warned these passengers that this active volcano was more likely than not going to erupt.  There had been warnings issued by several geological  organizations that said  that there was a danger of having this volcano erupt, but no one told the passengers.
and they've been sued. Royal Caribbean was sued here in the United States in federal district court.  Their defense was, look, we did operate the tour. If you want to sue the tour operator, go to New Zealand and good luck. But today, a federal judge here in South Florida said, oh no, Royal Caribbean, you have a responsibility, a legal duty under the law to  provide safety to your passengers, which includes the duty to warn them of dangers that you know or should have known of. And there was an increased likelihood
that this volcano was going to erupt and you didn't tell them. You sold them the tickets, you processed the tickets, you sold them through your excursion desk or online, and therefore you're responsible. So the case was not dismissed, which is great news for the survivors and the families of victims,  that they'll be able to hold the cruise line accountable here in federal court in Florida and not have to go to New Zealand and try to hold some tour operator responsible. This is an important lesson.
Tragic story, but an important lesson if you go on a cruise, always buy your excursions through the cruise line. Don't buy them independently to save a few shekels because the cruise line will be responsible if something goes wrong. And it often does. And  you don't want to be chasing down some zipline excursion operator in Roatan, Honduras. You want to be able to hold Carnival, Royal Caribbean, or Celebrity responsible if they sold you the excursion.
Very sad news for the victims, but good news that their families are going to get their day in court. Let me know what you think, and as always, have a safe cruise.

event: 80 Trump Ballots Burned
transcript:
Another state just banned former President Donald Trump from their 2024 ballot. The state is Maine, but the way this happened is very different than the way it happened last week in Colorado, where that state Supreme Court ruled that he should be removed for violation of the 14th Amendment. In Maine, the state law allows a Secretary of State to also weigh in on whether a candidate is eligible to be on the ballot, and that's what just happened.
Maine's Secretary of State Sheena Bellows just issued this 34 page ruling which says Trump is disqualified again because she found he violated the 14th Amendment. Secretary Bellows says initially three challenges were brought to her office by several Maine voters who said Trump should not be on the ballot for according to some of them violation of the 14th Amendment. There was a hearing on December 15th and all the parties involved presented exhibits and witnesses.
Trump's legal team filed a brief expressing his objection to being removed from Maine's ballot, but just moments ago, the Secretary of State ruled against him. Writing in her ruling, I conclude that Mr. Trump's primary petition is invalid. Specifically, I find that the declaration on his candidate consent form is false because he is not qualified to hold the office of president under Section 3 of the 14th Amendment. She goes on to say the applicability of Section 3 of the 14th Amendment
does not turn on whether an office seeker has been convicted of a crime. Now, if you actually read the 14th Amendment, Section 3, you can see it only says an office holder has violated the amendment if he or she has engaged in insurrection or given aid or comfort to someone engaged in insurrection. Now, in her ruling, Secretary Bellows goes through the state laws in Maine and the power given to her by the state legislature.
to manage the ballots for every election and decide which candidates meet the requirements to appear on those ballots by state law. It's also worth noting Republican Chris Christie was also disqualified for Maine's primary election ballot because he did not get the necessary signatures from Maine voters to qualify. Joe Biden, by the way, is not going to appear on New Hampshire's primary ballot because of a scuffle with that state over primary election dates. Now, obviously,
Former President Trump can appeal this main ruling to the courts, which he will obviously do,  and it will also give the United States Supreme Court even more reason to weigh in on the Colorado Supreme Court case as soon as possible, because there are several other states weighing this very same issue with the former president right now.

event: McDonald's Drink Cups Hold Same Amount of Liquid
transcript:
How long can a McDonalds paper cup actually hold liquid for? This video was posted to YouTube all the way back in 2020 by Photo-Al Timelapse. They filled up 3 different cups, one with Pepsi or Coke, one with water and one with orange juice. All of the cups contained ice as well, just like they would do at McDonalds. At around the 5 day mark, if you take a look at the orange juice, it's now turning mouldy. Now the description did say this isn't an attack at McDonalds, but rather just an observation.
At around the 40-50 day mark, the orange juice began to leak a little bit, however the coke hadn't budged. And then over very long space of time, from days 100 to 231, the coke cup finally gave in.

description: The moon, seen from the Arctic Circle, between Russia and Canada. It only lasts a few seconds, but it's worth seeing.  It's a spectacular sight.  Imagine that you are in a location between Canada and Russia and suddenly and for just 30 seconds, the moon appears in all its splendor and disappears before your eyes.   It looks like the moon is going to collide with the earth.   Even more impressive AND for just 5 seconds, a total eclipse of the sun takes place.   It's unprecedented and spectacular!     The video was shot in REAL-TIME. The phenomenon happens at the “perigee”:  the closest point of a heavenly body’s orbit around the Earth, where the proximity of the moon is so evident that, suddenly, we realize the great speed at which the Earth is moving.  This effect is only visible once a year and lasts for just 30 seconds… Astronomers figured out those exact 30 seconds and had the cameras rolling.  Fortunately they had a clear sky.  Amazing!  Watch this happen on the video. Total sun eclipse is ONLY 5 seconds….   #Space #Moon #Eclipse

The phenomenon happens at the “perigee”:  the closest point of a heavenly body’s orbit around the Earth, where the proximity of the moon is so evident that, suddenly, we realize the great speed at which the Earth is moving.  This effect is only visible once a year and lasts for just 30 seconds.  Astronomers figured out those exact 30 seconds and had the cameras rolling.  Fortunately they had a clear sky.  Amazing!  Watch this happen on the video.#sun #sunfunk #byronbyrd #universe #genshinimpact #moon#nasa

Every two years, engineering teams from around the world bring their solar powered EV creations together and pit them head to head over more than 3,000 kilometers or about 1860 miles. This year, 31 solar powered cars left the starting line. Only 12 reached the finish line.
First place in the Challenger class was Belgium's An Inoptis Infinite, with an average overall speed of about 55 miles per hour. The addition of a retractable fin at the top allowed the car to sail with the wind rather than fight against it. This may have helped the Inoptis solar team get the edge during reportedly high winds.”

event: a man rescuing a dog tied to train tracks right before it could hit both of them
transcript:
A man who dedicated his retirement to rescuing animals built a train for formerly stray dogs and became a dog train conductor. 88-year-old Eugene Bostic said that he didn't originally plan to spend his retirement this way, and it was just something that happened.
He lives on a large farm in Fort Worth, Texas, and unfortunately, a horse barn on his property became a local dumping spot for unwanted pets. Eugene and his brother Walter took the dogs in, giving them a safe place to live and proper care. Eugene was then inspired to create the dog train one day when he saw a neighbor using their tractor with carts attached to it to pull some large rocks. He looked at it and thought that something similar would be a perfect way to transport lots of dogs at once. And even though the dogs have lots of space to run and play,
the large farm. Eugene wanted to do something special for them and be able to take them on little field trips. So he took some plastic barrels with holes cut into the side and welded some wheels onto them and then tied them all together. He started taking the dogs on adventures along quiet streets and through the woods about twice a week. Eugene originally ran the train with the help of his brother Walter, but since Walter passed at the age of 91 in 2020, Eugene has been carrying on the mission himself. He said that he's not sure how long he'll continue to operate the train given his age, but the
the dogs really enjoy it and he'll do it for as long as he can. I'm Jen and I post something positive every day.

event: Pope Francis Disappears on Live TV
transcript: These are broadcast on TV to Catholics all over the world. But in April of 2020, one of these broadcasts made headlines for something strange occurring. After the Pope finishes his speech, he turns around to go back inside. But instead of walking away as normal, he appears to vanish into thin air. People slowed down the video and realized the Pope did seem to simply vanish. Some said this could have been edited, but this was being broadcast live.Theories quickly sprung up about this being a hologram and not the actual pope. Others thought maybe he's more divine than everyone expected and this was some kind of miracle. Some said that because this was during the pandemic, maybe he did not want to be out in public. So to make sure he was safe, they used a hologram instead. I find this unlikely, but how do you explain the pope disappearing? Some called this a glitch in the Matrix.

event: Boeing 737 plane crashed in China
transcript:
This morning, a catastrophic plane crash in southern China, showing a forest in flames, debris on the ground, smoke rising from the area where the Boeing 737 apparently went down. Chinese state media sharing pictures of the aftermath. China Eastern Flight 5735 left Kunming Airport just after 1 p.m. here, heading over the mountains of Yunnan Province toward Guangzhou, what was supposed to be less than a two-hour trip.
But the plane abruptly lost speed and altitude about 130 miles out according to flight data. China's civil aviation authority said radar contact was lost. Authorities confirm 123 passengers and nine crew on board. Emergency crews now scrambling to reach them. China Eastern Airlines turned its website dark with so little known about survivors. It's China's worst airline disaster in over a decade.
The country has a good aviation safety record that officials have credited to newer planes and strict flying rules. The China Eastern plane was a Boeing 737-89P that was just over six years old. For now, there is no information on the costs. Boeing has faced issues in the past over different planes. It's 737 MAXs, which were temporarily grounded in 2019 and 2020 after crashes.

description: Extremely rare white African wild dog puppy 4 Rivers is currently home to an extraordinary pack of wild dogs with a very leucistic pup. Local researchers have confirmed that this is extremely rare and virtually unheard of in Botswana for the past 30 years or so 🐾 In the 1990s, guides first spotted leucistic puppies in the Kwando area. The males of Kwando's pack have dispersed. These men, identified by photos, established a group dubbed the Golden Pack in the Vumbura area. Some descendants of this golden pack started another family in Kwara, where leucism was still evident but somewhat diluted. Leucism tends to be a lack of melanin in the skin, feathers, or hair. Melanin is the natural pigment responsible for most brown and black coloring. It is mostly genetic and varies in degree, going all the way to pure white in rare cases (like this one at 4 Rivers) or like in the "golden" Vumbura dogs, which are a pale tan tone. Currently, the pup interacts normally with its siblings and adult painted wolves (as African wild dogs are also known). Although this little one is anything but painted! If anything, it's dominant in the hierarchy when it comes to receiving food from adults! This pup may darken as he ages, and there is an outward chance that his whole body will be a large white spot, which sometimes happens with domestic dogs and cats. We'll keep a close eye to see how its color evolves 🐶 Thanks to the expert researchers in Botswana for their insight! Dr Peter Apps Dr John Tico McNutt Dr Gabriele Cozzi Botswana Predator Conservation

A study found that in 15 minutes of contact with hot liquids, leach 25,000 microplastic particles into your cup. But no one's questioning this. No one's really thinking about it, because it's just of our daily lives. Are we very good at metabolizing plastics? No. Plastic is a foreign body. It's a foreign particle. In fact, it'll break down into nanoplastics. And nanoparticles in general have the issue of being able to penetrate cell membranes. So it can penetrate very deeply into the cell. It can cause inflammation. Your body doesn't know how to deal with it. It's a foreign object. So you'll get the inflammatory response when you encounter these. But to make things worse, the microplastics themselves are a foreign body, but they also release plasticizer chemicals when they're in contact with your body. And they can also carry toxichemicals into your body. The fact that they can basically invade and integrate into our cells and you are what you eat. Are we turning into real life Barbie kenndalls? event: Anavid Reyes 'Traffic Reporter Meltdown'
transcript:
Traffic anchor Anna V. Reyes has a look at this weekend's traffic. Yes, Veronica, we are out here live. We are at exit 57 on I-24 East. If you look at the traffic, don't expect too many delays. As you can see out here, things look to be moving along just fine. 

Over my left shoulder, you can see some minor road construction in the area, but that hasn't affected things much this morning. And oh, by the way, just real quick, my name is pronounced Anavid, not Anavid. 

So if I'm going to come out here and do these live traffic reports and literally risk my life, I'd appreciate it if somebody back in the studio could learn how to pronounce my name. Oh, I'm sorry. You got it, Anavid. 

And what's it look like southbound? I mean, just like in the grand scheme of life, think about what we're doing right now. I'm doing a live traffic report on television. This traffic report is going to be obsolete in three minutes. 

I mean, I have a report that there's construction in the area, obviously, as you know, but there's a wreck about a mile ahead. And so this is going to be, all this traffic is going to be changed in literally about 60 seconds. 

It looks like you've got an inside source on that wreck. Have you been in contact with the police chief? Have I talked to the police chief? No, I have not. I've actually just literally looked on Google Maps. 

And every time you guys send me out of here for a live traffic report, I literally just look on Google Maps. Oh, look, traffic. I look on Google Maps and report to you what I see here. And I don't know if you guys knew this back at the station, but every person in America has access to this. 

Well, it looks cold. And it sounds like you may have woken up on the wrong side of the bed. Yeah, I don't know. Or woken up on the wrong side of the bed, or most people are still in bed because no one's watching the local news for traffic. 

Like in terms of figuring out the best route to work and traffic patterns, I can think of off the top of my head, 57 other ways to do this more efficiently. Google Maps, Apple Maps, Bing Maps. My uncle Ricky still has a TomTom. 

He could plug the address into that. I don't know. Go to a truck stop and rent a CV and talk to one of these truck drivers. He could probably tell you a better way to know what the traffic is. I mean, I'm just trying to figure out why. 

Thank you, Anna V.

The video shows the footage of Bigfoot being caught on Drone and a man explaining saying “Taking a look at some groundbreaking footage of the infamous Bigfoot.
A man was flying around his drone one day. He was flying it over the woods, attempting to get some really cool footage of the forest and the wildlife. But what he eventually captured was not at all what he expected. As he flew the drone above the trees, he unintentionally captures what could be some of the most convincing evidence of Bigfoot ever. A hairy bipedal creature is seen making its way down the snowy path. It leisurely walks along, unaware of the presence of the drone above. Skeptics immediately tried to debunk the footage by calling the creature a gorilla.
But the way this thing walks is just so human. You can tell when it's a gorilla or primate by the way they hunch over when they walk around. And judging by this walk here, this doesn't look like one at all. Also, we need to consider the fact that the footage was taken somewhere in the US and the US is not home to any primates. So I'll leave this one up to you, the viewers.
Is this real footage of Bigfoot?”

description: #Repost @facesofhaiti ... Thank you Dr Berthrude Albert for bringing this back to our attention  @bertrhude. On Feb. 10, 2010 President Bill Clinton, then the UN Special Envoy to Haiti, publicly apologized for forcing Haiti to drop tariffs on imported, subsidized US rice during his time in office.  The policy wiped out Haitian rice farming and seriously damaged Haiti’s ability to be self-sufficient. [ Transcript ] “Since 1981, the United States has followed a policy, until the last year or so when we started rethinking it, that we rich countries that produce a lot of food should sell it to poor countries and relieve them of the burden of producing their own food, so, thank goodness, they can leap directly into the industrial era. It has not worked. It may have been good for some of my farmers in Arkansas, but it has not worked. It was a mistake. It was a mistake that I was a party to. I am not pointing the finger at anybody. I did that. I have to live every day with the consequences of the lost capacity to produce a rice crop in Haiti to feed those people, because of what I did. transcript:
The video shows a woman saying “In 2010, Bill Clinton publicly apologized for destroying Haiti rice industry. Heres what happened. Before the 1980s, Haiti was self sufficient in food consumption. We didn't depend on other nations in order to feed ourselves. For example, 90% of the rice consumed in Haiti was grown locally in the Atkabunet area. For a long time, the IMF and the US Government were trying to change that by pressuring Haiti to lower tariffs on agricultural products. Haiti had high tariffs or taxes on imported food, which protected locally grown agriculture. Although experts warned that lowering the tariffs would be disastrous for Haiti, it was also clear that these lower tariffs would be a benefit to the United States. U.S. farmers were able to get rid of their surplus crops. They took everything they weren't able to sell in America and they dumped it in Haiti under the guise of food aid.
This was possible because in 1991, there was a quiditta overthrowing the Haitian president Alistid. Although the US played a role in the quiditta, they agreed to help restore Alistid to power if he would agree to a couple of things, like lowering the rice tariff. In exchange for political and financial support. The Clinton administration was able to force Haiti to make a decision that ultimately would destroy our rice industry. In 1995, after being pressured by the Clinton administration and the IMF, Haiti decided to lower the tariff on rice from 50% to 3%, the lowest in the Caribbean. A surge of rice poured into Haiti every year. The US Government began paying US Farmers hundreds of millions of dollars from US aid in order to give their excess rice to Haiti.
Most of the imported rice came from Arkansas, Clinton's home state. And so Clinton's farmers benefited greatly while Haitian farmers completely lost their livelihoods. That's why in his apology, Clinton said it may have been good for some of his farmers in Arkansas.
Despite his apology, the impact is still there. Haiti still has the lowest tariff on rice in the Caribbean. And Haiti is now the 5th largest importer of American rice in the world.
Instead of us producing 90% of the rice we consume, we're importing 90% of the rice we consume. This is why initiatives like the Canal are so important. We're rebuilding what has been destroyed. And so we say Canala Pop Compet.”

transcript: This is the first known footage of the Titanic at the bottom of the ocean floor. It was taken in 1986. And now, for the first time, much of the footage has been released to the public. After the ocean liner sank during its 1912 Maide in Voyage, researchers spent decades looking for the wreckage. Finally, in 1985, the downship was found more than 12,000ft below the surface by the Woods Hole oceanic institution expedition. Lee Dr. Robert Ballard described his first time seeing the ship as spooky. After hitting the iceberg, the Titanic broke in half. The stern roughly tumbled through the water before slamming into the ocean floor so hard that every deck was flattened. However, the bow struck the ocean floor at such an angle that large sections of the interior remained intact. Ballard, who first took photos of the ship when his team discovered it in 1985, returned nine months later to capture it on video. Using a human occupied submersible named Alvin in a remotely operated vehicle named Jason Jr. The team was able to film the wreckage for the first time. The footage is being publicly released now to coincide with and celebrate the 25th anniversary of James Cameron's epic 1997 film Titanic.

event: 'Child Militia' Deployed in Atlanta
transcript:
Do you all remember the story of Wayne Williams and the Atlanta child murders? From 1979 to 1981, there are about 29 murders in the Atlanta area that appear to be linked. Most of the victims were boys and all of them were black. The majority were young and some were even children. The community then named the killing spree the Atlanta child murders. The first victims of the Atlanta child murders were two boys, one 14 and the other 13.
both of whom disappeared within three days of each other. Both were found dead on the side of the road beside each other on July 28th, 1978. One was shot while the other was strangled to death. From there, bodies continued to pile up. By March 1980, the death toll had reached at least six. Every lead in the Atlanta child murder case turned up to be nothing for local authorities. Before long, it was time for the FBI to step in.
famous FBI profiler John Douglas weighed in on a potential killer profile of the Atlanta murders culprit.  He had already devoted much of his work to interviewing serial killers and assassins.  So it's no surprise that Douglas had a hunch about this particular case.  In his case files on the Atlanta child murders,  Douglas reported that he believes the murderer was someone black and not white.  He theorized that in order to have access to black children, the Atlanta killer would need access to the black community without any suspicion.
By late May of 1981,  many of the dead bodies linked to the case had been recovered within the same geographic parameters.  Some had been pulled out of the Chattahoochee River,  so investigators staked out its bridges.  That's when they found Wayne Williams, who was awfully close to where Nathaniel Carter's body was later discovered.  The body of 21-year-old Jimmy Ray Payne was also found, apparently allowing cops to build their case.
It wasn't until June 21st, about a month after the discoveries of the bodies, that police were able to arrest Wayne Williams.  He was cuffed after it was found that his alibis were fake  and he failed a polygraph test. Police  also had collected fibers from Williams' car and his family dogs.  These same fibers were found on both Carter and Payne's bodies.
In February, 1982, Williams was convicted and subsequently handed two life sentences for the murders of Payne and Carter.  Williams was never convicted of the rest of the murders in the Atlanta child murders case,  but local police alleged that he was responsible for them.  However, some Atlanta residents, including relatives of the Atlanta child murders victims, believe he did not commit those crimes.  Wayne has consistently maintained his innocence ever since he was put in jail decades ago.
In one 1991 interview, Williams said he accepts his fate and that God has a plan for him.

But what's also important is what the justices did not say. So first, I'm going to tell you what they did say. Unanimously, the Supreme Court ruled in a short 13-page ruling that the Colorado Supreme Court went too far when it ruled that former President Trump could not appear on Colorado's ballot because he's an insurrectionist and he violated Section 3 of the 14th Amendment. The Supreme Court said no.
When it comes to the office of the president, the majority of the Supreme Court ruled today that determining whether someone violated the 14th Amendment is a job for Congress.
Essentially, the justices rule today that when states ratified the 14th Amendment back in 1868, which prohibits insurrectionists from holding office, they didn't really say how those insurrectionists should be prevented from holding office. Today, the justices said it should be up to Congress to decide how that process works. If Congress wants to pass a law that says, yeah, states do have the power to remove a candidate because he or she is an insurrectionist and violates the 14th Amendment, then they can do that. Or if Congress wants to pass a law that says only Congress can decide that, they can do that too. But until Congress says something about it, the states cannot make this decision on their own. The Supreme Court says, States have no power under the Constitution to enforce Section 3 with respect to federal offices, especially the presidency. However, the Supreme Court said states can enforce the 14th Amendment if the person involved is running for a state office. Now to what the Supreme Court did not say today. They did not rule on whether or not former President Trump is an insurrectionist. This ruling actually says nothing about that. The justices also did not say anything about whether a candidate running for the office of president of the United States is subject to the 14th Amendment. Former President Trump was trying to argue that the president is not an officer of the United States. Therefore, the 14th Amendment does not apply to him.
The Supreme Court actually said nothing about that either. It's also important to understand that while the three liberal justices did sign on to this majority opinion, they wrote what's called a concurring opinion, which says the majority went too far when they said it's up to Congress to decide how to apply the 14th Amendment. The liberal justices say that's a step too far because there may be other ways the 14th Amendment could be imposed on those holding or attempting to hold federal office. So if you want to read this short 13-page ruling from the Supreme Court, I will email it out to you tonight in my News Girl News Roundup email. So make sure you sign yourself up.”

description: The Supreme Court on Monday restored Donald Trump to 2024 presidential primary ballots, rejecting state attempts to hold the Republican former president accountable for the Capitol riot. The justices ruled a day before the Super Tuesday primaries that states cannot invoke a post-Civil War constitutional provision to keep presidential candidates from appearing on ballots. That power resides with Congress, the court wrote in an unsigned opinion. The outcome ends efforts in Colorado, Illinois, Maine and elsewhere to kick Trump, the front-runner for his party's nomination, off the ballot because of his attempts to undo his loss in the 2020 election to Democrat Joe Biden, culminating in the Jan. 6, 2021, attack on the Capitol. For more, go to CP24.com

event: Environmental activist Greta Thunberg admitted that the climate crisis wasn't real
transcript: The video shows Greta Thunberg, a Swedish Climate Activist, talking in the news and saying “If I speak for myself I don’t think I thought that this was going to lead to something real because let’s face it, as long as we continue to ignore the vast majority of this crisis, as long as our main goal is to find loopholes and find excuses not to take real action, then we will most likely not see any big results at these meetings. There needs to be a big public pressure from the outside and that is not what it is right now. People in power can still do almost whatever they want as long as they say some nice words and talk about coalitions and alliances, building alliances fighting ‘climate change’, then they get away with it because they are not being held accountable. Some people seem to say that it’s a success, that we are making progress, but then when you actually speak to the people who are been present there, the people who are watching what is happening, it’s a completely different story. That it’s still fighting between each other, and that especially the least affected countries, so-called developed countries, are still refusing to do even the bare minimum. So, of course, that may not be considered a success. There is still a very, very long way to go. Voices from activists of the most affected areas are still not being heard enough. We need much more representation to be present everywhere, but especially at the conference like the COP26 .

description: Squirrel nut burial strategy depends on species, nut-type, and the likelihood other squirrels will come for their nuts #sciencetok #squirrelsoftiktok #animalscience #terminalvelocity
user_description: I summarize my best science and progress content in my weekly newsletter:
event: a squirrel defecating, only for the feces to fly through the air and land on another nearby squirrel
transcript: Not only can squirrels survive falling from any height because their terminal velocity is slow enough, but socioeconomics are at play when it comes to deciding where to bury their nuts. They can bury up to 3,000 nuts in a single season, and their method depends on the species. So American red squirrels bury al their nuts at the base of a single tree, which makes it easier to defend from other squirrels. That's called the central bank or larder hoarding. My favorite is the mixed strategy where squirrels will organize their caches by the nut type. So they'll have the almonds in one area, the acorns in another area, and the peanuts in another area. I just think that's so cute. My final and favorite method is the scatter hoarding method, which is like the information economy, where squirrels that forage over a wider area will plant the nuts closer to where they're found, both to avoid bringing them back to a central location and to avoid other squirrels finding their stashes. They also regularly dig fake holes to throw the other squirrels off and re dig up their own buried nuts throughout the winter and replant them in other spots so they don't forget where they planted them. They're like rehearsing. Inevitably, some nuts are never found, and they grow into a new generation of especially oak, walnut, and hickory trees to feed the next generation of local squirrels. These are my sources, and if you liked this, I have a weekly newsletter. The link is in my bio.

description: Mystery rocket hits The Moon!!🚀🌚👽🤖 Follow for more!!! #Fyp #Moon #OuterSpace
user_description: DJ/Producer/PartyThrower 🤟😝
event: rocket hitting the moon
transcript:
Humans last visited the moon in 1972 and haven't returned ever since. It's been half a century.
This rocky visitor to our night sky remains a fairly unfamiliar place with many unresolved mysteries.  The latest one has left scientists baffled.
A group of researchers from Arizona say that a mystery rocket crashed on the moon in the month of March.  No one knows where it came from or what it looked like,  whether it was meant for the moon or spiraled out of trajectory.
But a rocket crashed for sure.  It struck the fair side of the moon at 7.25 a.m. Eastern time on March 4th.  The crash site was the Hepsprang Crater, a 350-mile wide basin  that's out of sight of anyone on Earth.  And here's the most intriguing bit.  The impact of the crash created not one, but two craters.  This is unusual by scientific standards.
No other rocket crash on the moon has created double craters,  not once in history.  Scientists say this may be because the rocket had large masses at each end,  but this too  is unusual. Typically, a rocket has mass concentrated at the mortar end. The rest of the body consists of an empty fuel tank.  So the mystery persists.  No one on Earth is owning up and the speculation is falling flat.  At first,
Scientists say the rocket was the second stage  of a SpaceX Falcon 9 launched in 2015.  But its trajectory was found incompatible and the theory was junked.  After more digging, scientists say it was a Long March  3C rocket launched from China way back in October 2014.  Beijing has denied this.  It said  that rocket had re-entered the Earth's atmosphere and burned up.
So  all we have  are false positives.  What will it take to solve this mystery?  Time.  The researchers who made this discovery say they need more time to feel the gums.  To find out if the rocket was launched by humans  or  by an extraterrestrial species.

If it's not absorbing water, then that means there must be a barrier in between the paper and the liquid. And that barrier is polyethylene plastic. A study found that in 15 minutes of contact with hot liquids, leached 25,000 microplastic particles into your cup. But no one's questioning this. No one's really thinking about it because it's just part of our daily lives. Are we very good at metabolizing plastics? No. Plastic is a foreign body. It's a foreign particle. In fact, it'll break down into nanoplastics. And nanoparticles in general have the issue of being able to penetrate cell membranes. So it can penetrate very deeply into the cell. It can cause inflammation. Your body doesn't know how to deal with it. It's a foreign object. So you'll get the inflammatory response when you encounter these. But to make things worse, the microplastics themselves are a foreign body, but they also release plasticizer chemicals when they're in contact with your body. And they can also carry toxic chemicals into your body. The fact that they can basically invade and integrate into ourselves and you are what you eat, are we turning into real life Barbie and Candles? Malaysia's Transport Minister Anthony Locke announced on Sunday, March 3, that Malaysia is advocating for a fresh search effort for Malaysia's Airlines Flight MH370  as the 10th anniversary of its vanishing,  marking one of aviation's most significant mysteries draws near. Initially, Malaysian investigators didn't dismiss the notion of deliberate diversion of the aircraft's course, while debris including some confirmed and suspected pieces from the plane
surface along Africa's coast and Indian Ocean Island. In 2018, Malaysia enlisted Ocean Infinity to explore the southern Indian Ocean with a pledge of up to $70 million for locating the aircraft. Prior to this, Malaysia, China, and Australia terminated a fruitless two-year $200 million Australian underwater search in January 2017. Anthony Loeck mentioned that the US seabed exploration company Ocean Infinity
has been approached to discuss the latest search plan following two unsuccessful efforts. He added that Malaysia intends to engage with Australia regarding collaboration for resuming the search once Ocean Infinity's proposal receives approval from Malaysia's cabinet. On March 8, 2014, flight MH370 of Boeing 777 with 227 passengers and 12 crew members on board disappeared while flying from Kuala Lumpur
to Beijing.  This year marks its 10th anniversary of aircraft's disappearance.

event: Invisibility Cloak
transcript:
Ever wondered what you would do if you could simply disappear into thin air? Imagine the possibilities. The world of science fiction has long toyed with the concept of invisibility, but today, we're stepping into reality. In a recent reveal that seems straight out of a Harry Potter novel, China has unveiled an invisible cloak.  Yes, you heard it right.  An invisible cloak. This isn't a magic trick or a clever camera angle.  It's a real tangible product of cutting edge technology.  Now you might be asking yourself,
how does an invisible cloak work?  Well, it's all about bending light.  The cloak uses a complex array of lenses and reflectors to bend light around an object,  effectively rendering it invisible to the naked eye.  Think of it like water flowing around a rock in a stream. The water doesn't stop, it simply goes around the rock. Similarly, the light doesn't stop, it just bends around the object.  This innovation is a game changer, not just for the world of espionage or defense,  but for numerous other fields as well.  Think about it.
Wildlife photographers could get closer to their subjects without disturbing them.  Researchers could observe natural behavior more accurately, and the list goes on.  But every coin has two sides.  While the advantages are numerous, the ethical implications of such technology are also worth considering.  Invisibility could potentially be misused in the wrong hands, leading to a whole new set of challenges.  It's a classic case of technology outpacing our ability to fully comprehend its implications.  To sum it up,
The invisible cloak is here,  and it's as mind-boggling as it sounds.  It's a testament to human innovation and the relentless pursuit of knowledge.  Yet it's also a reminder of the responsibility we carry to use such advancements wisely. After all, with great power comes great responsibility. So, in the world where invisibility is no longer just a science fiction dream, let's remember to keep our eyes wide open to the possibilities and implications it brings along.
After all what we can't see can indeed change the world.

event: Amy Roloff died in mid-November 2022
transcript: Amy Roloff and her husband Chris from the show Little People Big World met at a party. They've been together for seven years now. Recently, they celebrated their second wedding anniversary. Amy shared a bunch of photos on social media. It's amazing to think that seven years have gone by since she went on her first bike ride with him. After Matt's ex-wife divorced him, she started spending time with other single people. She went on a date with a man named Bob to a painting event in Portland. There, she met Chris and they started talking. Later on, Chris went to a pool party but seemed a bit shy. This was shown on the TV show Little People, Big World during the 16th season. He then took her for a bike ride, and three years after that, they went on a long road trip together on his bike. Amy Roloff and Chris just seemed to get along really well. Fans of the show were excited and hoped they would get engaged and married. However, the wedding didn't happen as quickly as some impatient TLC fans hoped. The star of Little People, Big World took two years after getting engaged to finally have the wedding. This delay was because she had to move into a new home and save enough money for both the new house and the wedding. Eventually, they got married at Roloff Farms two years ago. On August 28th, the TLC personality posted numerous pictures on her Instagram of her and Chris. Some were taken during their trips, while others displayed them having fun on the beaches of the Pacific Northwest. Along with the photos, the main figure of little people, Big World wrote, Happy second anniversary, Chris, my love. I adore our amazing, sometimes wild and busy, yet simple life that we're living together. Amy Roloff then shared about their meeting many years ago. She went on to say, met seven years ago and now look where we are. Chris, I love you not only today but also all of my tomorrows. Here's to us. Predictably, many people quickly sent their congratulations to the couple, as Chris as well liked. Naturally, they are delighted to see his wife so joyful. Amy Roloff's post received over 20,000 likes in just a few hours, and there were already close to a thousand comments. Besides sending their congratulations, some fans shared kind words with them. One fan commented, Happy anniversary to you both! Another follower wrote, Happy anniversary to you and Chris! Hope that you enjoy this sweet day to the fullest together! Do you agree that Amy seems happier since she met Chris Merck? Can you believe that it's already been two years since they got married after knowing each other for seven years? Share your thoughts in the comments below and stay tuned here for more updates on little people. Big world!

event: Minecraft Shutting Down in 2020
transcript: Many of the most popular Minecraft Java multiplayer servers have been shutting down lately, with the most recent one being Mindplex. Mindplex abruptly closed last month because the server began to run out of money since the player base has been declining for many years now. Other servers like MC Gamer Network, which which home to Minecraft Hunger Games, had its farewell event in 2020, and then after 8 years of running a Hive MC, which was another multiplayer server, closed in 2021. Primary reason these servers are closing is because the servers couldn't afford to run the server since a lot of people aren't playing anymore, which is very unfortunate because this was a lot of our childhoods, and to see them go is truly the end of an era.

event: Drone Delivering Instant Noodles
transcript: This is how Drone Delivery works this is a Wing delivery drone. It's 11 pounds and can deliver packages within a six mile radius of its home base, in this case Walmart and the Dallas area. You may not have this in your area just yet, but for people living in the Dallas area or in Christiansburg, Virginia, it is totally normal to see a drone deliver a package in your neighborhood. Here's how it works. The drones sit here on their charging pads in their nest waiting for an order. Once someone places an order in the Wing Delivery app, the order is packed in this tote. The dread will take off from its pad and let down this yellow clip which an employee will use to attach the tote. This was incredible incred fun to do by the way. I had to go through training to do this. And finally the drone will deliver the package within 30 minutes or less from the time of ordering. So you might think, wow, an invention for incredibly lazy people. Yeah, maybe. But consider this. You're in the middle of a science experiment and you'forgotten one ingredient. Or maybe you need ice cream or snacks for a movie. Or maybe for one reason or another, physically going to the store is a little bit hard for you and you just needed a couple things. Drone delivery is useful in all of these cases and it benefits the rest of us by removing vehicles from the road that would normally be delivering these items. After all, you shouldn't need a two ton vehicle to deliver a two ounce bottle of medicine. Right now it is totally free to customers. So what do you think? Would you use the service? That was awesome.

It's a different argument for medical delivery though, which provides life-saving support every day in many countries across Africa. Australian operator Swoop Aero has been delivering medical items across Africa for years now. transcript: This is a TikTok for people in Pennsylvania. If you're not from Pennsylvania, you can still watch it, but this isn't for you. The Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled yesterday that any mail in ballots that are incorrectly dated or do not have a date written on the envelope will not be counted. Even if they are submitted by or on election Day. They will not be counted if they do not have the correct date written on the envelope. Why? Wait, actually, why? I mean, it makes no sense. If they're still receiving the ballots by election Day, then they know that the ballots came in on time regardless of what the date on the envelope says. And it's not like a fake date can change a vote. I mean, everyone still gets one vote. It's just people who accidentally get their dates wrong don't get their vote counted. And how do they tell if a date is incorrect? I mean, if they're counting all the votes at the same time, then how would they be able to tell if a vote came in one day earlier versus one day later? I mean, maybe they separate the ballots based on what day they were received or what day they were submitted. But if that's the case, then isn't the date sort of unnecessary because they already know which day the ballot was received? Sorry, I got carried away there. Let's just look at the rules. Like, what constitutes an incorrect date? I do not know. I looked thoroughly on the official voting website for Pennsylvania. All it said was that you have to sign and date the declaration on your envelope. That's all the guidance they give you. So I'm assuming it means the day that you fill out your ballot. But what if you decide to submit your ballot the day after you fill it out, which is what I did. Does that mean you have to write a different date? And what if you write your dates the European way, where the day is first and the month is second? I'm advising you to please write it the American way, just in case your vote doesn't get counted otherwise. But this just seems like a weird way to throw out a lot of votes from people who are just as confused as me. So, please, if you live in Pennsylvania, write the date that you fill out your ballot very carefully. Make sure to get it correct based on the next to zero guidance that the state of Pennsylvania has given you. Because I want your vote to count. event: Heath Ledger Hidden in 'Dark Knight' Scene
transcript: In preparation for his role as the Joker in The Dark Knight, Heath Ledger hid away in a motel room for about six weeks. During this extended stay of seclusion, Ledger delved deep into the psychology of the character. He devoted himself to developing the Joker's every tick, namely the voice and that sadistic sounding laugh. For the voice, Ledger's goal was to create a tone that didn't echo the work Jack Nicholson did in his 1989 performance as the Joker. Ledger's interpretation of the Joker's appearance was primarily based on the chaotic, disheveled look of punk rocker Sid Vicious, combined with the psychotic mannerisms of Malcolm McDowell's character Alex Delarge from O'Clockwork Orange.

event: a New Species of 'Green' Capybara was Discovered in 2021
transcript: Capobaras are semi-thequatic animals native to South America. They are found in a variety of habitats such as savannas, forests and wetlands throughout most of South America, including countries such as Brazil, Venezuela, Colombia, Peru and Argentina. They are especially abundant in the Amazon basin, but can also be found in other areas such as the Pantanal wetlands in Brazil and the Anoes grasslands in Venezuela and Colombia. Capobaras are also popular as domesticated pets in some parts of the world. Capobaras are excellent swimmers and are often found in or near water. In fact, they are semi-aquatic animals, which means that they spend a significant amount of time in water to keep cool, to escape predators and to find food. Capobaras have webbed feet and can hold their breath underwater for up to five minutes. They are also able to swim quickly and easily, making them well adapted to their semi-aquatic lifestyle. In addition to swimming, Capobaras also enjoy soaking in water to regulate their body temperature and to clean their fur.

transcript:
Back now with our NBC News exclusive as the GOP presidential candidates prepare to meet on our stage here in Miami on Wednesday. One of them, Ron DeSantis, is getting a major boost as Iowa's governor makes a rare endorsement. 

Both spoke with Dasha Burns. Tonight, Governor Kim Reynolds explaining why she's breaking with the Iowa tradition of staying neutral and endorsing Ron DeSantis. I just felt like I couldn't sit on the sidelines any longer. 

We have too much at stake. I truly believe that he is the right person to get this country back on track. It's arguably the biggest endorsement of the primary and a much-needed win for the DeSantis campaign, which has invested significant time and resources here. 

This one's obviously very meaningful because Kim has proven to be a great leader that Iowans love. With two months to go, former President Trump maintains a dominant 27-point lead among likely Iowa caucus goers, with DeSantis and Nikki Haley tied for second. 

For those who criticize you and say, why are you endorsing a guy who's been slipping in the polls? Trump is 30 points ahead. What do you say to those critics? I don't base my decision on polls. I take a look at who I believe is the right person for the right job. 

I believe that Ron is the right person for the right job, and I believe he's going to win. Do you worry about the risk that she's taking by endorsing you? No, I don't. I mean, first of all, I respect the fact that that's not her calculation, which is rare amongst elected officials. 

I've had people come to me and say, you know, that they endorsed him because of the threats and everything like that. If you can look in the mirror and say you did what you think is right for the right reasons, then just let the chips fall where they may. 

Mr. Trump was quick to attack Governor Reynolds for her endorsement, calling her America's most unpopular governor. What is your relationship like now with the former president? Well, you know, I assume it's, well, I don't know. 

I really can't tell you. That's probably a question for him. Have you spoken with him recently? No, I haven't. When's the last time? Probably the last time he called to ask if I would endorse him, and I said I wasn't at this point. 

The question now of her endorsement of DeSantis will make a difference. I just hope that'll help persuade some of those voters to take a look at him closer. Does it impact my vote? I don't know for sure at this point. 

He's been on my radar, so I maybe I'll feel like I know a little bit more after the debate. Do you believe Trump can't win? Yeah, I believe he can't win, and I believe Ron can. If DeSantis wants to prove Trump is beatable, he'll have to do it here. 

Dasha Burns, NBC News, Des Moines, Iowa. Thanks for watching. Stay updated about breaking news and top stories on the NBC News app or follow us on social media.

event: a Boston Dynamics Robot demonstrating fighting skills
transcript: The video shows a man explaining the Boston Dynamics Atlas Robot saying “ we’re not just thinking about how to make the robot move dynamically through its environment like we did in parkour and dance. Now we’re starting to put ATLAS to work and think about how the robot should be able to perceive and manipulate objects in its environment while maintaining that characteristic high-level of performance that we expect from Atlas. Carefully considering the forces that exist between the robot and the object and how that might or might not tip the robot over for example is really important to success. It’s already hard for a robot to know where it is so when we’re trying to manipulate something  like a plank, we have to just make pretty educated guesses about. Where is the plank? How fast is it moving? How do we need to move the arms to cause the plank to spin 180° very quickly and if we get those estimates wrong, we end up doing silly things and falling over. We can explore all those questions in the simulator and then we can test them on the real Hardware and often those test in the real world will result in a broken robot, which is fine. We can fix it, but if we want to push the boundaries, we can do that in SIM first.

description: Boston Dynamics’ Robot Atlas shows off human-like skills. The Atlas robot can now run, jump, pick up, throw heavy objects and perform complex moves that may one day help humans in factories or on construction sites.  The video released titled “Atlas Gets a Grip” displays the Atlas robot picking up not only the tool bag but also a larger wooden plank to make it’s way up the stairs and jumping in between levels without loosing it’s balance. The Atlas finished off with an incredible complex 540-degree, multi-axis flip.  Unlike Boston Dynamics’ four-legged Spot robot, Atlas is not commercially available. The technology team hopes to eventually give robots the technological capabilities to “perform real, physical demanding jobs with hustle”.  #atlas #robots #technews #bostondynamics

War in Gaza, day 94, and the IDF maneuvers in southern Gaza are continuing to make progress.  The army says that in the past 24 hours, dozens of terrorists were killed in clashes in and around Khan Yunis, where Hamas leadership is hiding in underground tunnels and bunkers.  Over 100 targets were hit in and around the city, including weapons caches and terror tunnels.  Among those killed, the grandson of Hamas founder, Sheikh Yassin.
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu told the cabinet that Israel is not yet ready to wind down its war against Hamas  even as international pressure mounts for a shift by Israel  to lower intensity fighting to avoid civilian casualties.
In the north, Hezbollah rocket fire has damaged the Mount Maron air traffic control base near the Lebanese border.  The army confirmed that the site's radar domes were hit by missiles on Saturday, but the facility is now working on backup systems.  Hezbollah fired a barrage of more than 40 rockets and several missiles at the base atop Mount Maron,  which is located some 8 kilometers from the Lebanon border.  Hezbollah said the attack was a response to the alleged Israeli killing of Hamas terror chief
Salih al-Aruri in Lebanon last week.  The IDF is investigating the incident in order to prevent similar attacks on the sensitive base.  In response, the IDF said it carried out several waves of strikes on Hezbollah targets in Lebanon,  including two significant military compounds belonging to the terror group.  IDF Chief of Staff Halevi said that the military was exacting increasingly heavy prices on Hezbollah as it continued to carry out attacks on northern Israel.
U.S. Secretary of State Blinken is due to arrive in Israel this evening on his fifth visit to the country since the start of the war on October 7th.  Blinken will arrive after talks in Qatar, where its prime minister said that the killing of Hamas deputy commander Al-Aurore in Beirut last week has affected Doha's ability to mediate between the terror group and Israel over the release of hostages and ceasefire efforts. But the Gulf state's political leader said that Qatar will continue its efforts.
He also said that hostilities along the Red Sea shipping route are unacceptable  and an unfortunate effect of the war in Gaza.  Blinken warned that the war between Israel and Hamas in Gaza could metastasize and threaten security in the wider Middle East.  This is a moment of profound tension in the region that could lead to even more insecurity and even more suffering, Blinken said.
